Comment:
Elements of Iran Contra get the big screen treatment.  

Seal was no joke.  He was a major supplier, courier if you will, of coke that was 
processed into crack.  Seal was in the right place at the right time, 
same with Freeway Ricky Ross.  They both made serious money off the 
crack trade that was just starting to get rolling in the early 1980s in 
major cities across the country that were beginning to feel the sting of
 deindustrialization and the impending low-wage, underemployment 
economy. 

Mena Arkansas was a frequent drug drop site, I presume the 
movie will touch on this.  The drugs, tons of cash and gun running that 
Seal and some others (there were others) were hauling was basically 
controlled by elements of the CIA to get around the Boland Amendment.
¬†
During the 1970s and early 1980s indigenous-populist movements in 
Central America were gaining power by serving the people.  For decades 
El Salvador and Nicaragua (and some of the other C. American states) were lorded over by corrupt and violent kleptocrats.  By the mid/late 1970s populist movements fighting for economic justice were starting to gain ground.  The Washington imperialists 
feared these democratic movements like the plague, see, the kleptocrats 
were always under Washington's thumb; opening their states up to 
corporate capitalist penetration.  Since these long over due populist 
movements sent such fear into the ruling class in Washington, Ollie and 
the boys along with covert CIA operatives started running guns to 
mercenaries to fight the guerrillas who were a part of the populist 
movements.  The Contras were some of these mercenaries.  They were directly responsible for some of the most heinous torture and murder of innocent civilians that the Western hemisphere has ever witnessed: castrating children in front of their parents, then cutting off heads of parents in front of children, it's all documented and sickening beyond belief.  American tax dollars were indirectly supporting all this and the US coke market was directly involved in it.

Anytime the powers that be need to wage a clandestine war 
(work around the Boland Amendment and domestic public opinion) they of course need to drum up cash, lots of cash.  That's where Seal, the coke and the boyz came in.  

I'll be very interested to see how candid this movie is about the role of the 
national security state imperialists in Washington, sometimes now 
referred to as the "Deep State."  

For further reading on what I've quickly sketched out above: see the works by Gary Webb, Nicholas Shou, Robert Parry, and Cockburn and St. Clair's book 'Whiteout'.  For a 
deeper understanding of the progressive movements in Central America in 
the 1970s and early '80s, see the books and articles by James Petras, 
Michael Parenti and Noam Chomsky.  Also see the dynamite movies 
"Salvador" by Oliver Stone, and the film "Romero."

Title: American Made - Official Trailer [HD]
Comment: Elements of Iran Contra get the big screen treatment.  Seal was no joke.  He was a major, major supplier, courier if you will, of coke that was processed into crack.  Seal was in the right place at the right time, same with Freeway Ricky Ross.  They both made serious money off the crack trade that was just starting to get rolling in the early 1980s in major cities across the country that were beginning to feel the sting of deindustrialization and the impending low-wage, underemployment economy. Mena Arkansas was a frequent drug drop site, I presume the movie will touch on this.  The drugs, tons of cash and gun running that Seal and some others (there were others) were hauling was basically controlled by elements of the CIA to get around the Boland Amendment.  During the 1970s and early 1980s indigenous-populist movements in Central America were gaining power by serving the people.  For decades El Salvador and Nicaragua were lorded over by corrupt and violent kleptocrats.  By the late 1970s populist movements fighting for economic justice were starting to gain ground.  The Washington imperialists feared these democratic movements like the plague, see, the kleptocrats were always under Washington's thumb; opening their countires up to corporate capitalist penetration.  Since these long over due populist movements sent such fear into the ruling class in Washington, Ollie and the boys along with covert CIA operatives started running the guns to mercenaries to fight the guerrillas who were a part of the populist movements.  Anytime the powers that be need to wage a clandestine war (work around the Boland Amendment) they of course need to drum up cash, lots of cash.  That's where Seal and the boyz came in.  I'll be very interested to see how candid this movie is about the role of the national security state imperialists in Washington, sometimes now referred to as the "Deep State."  For further reading on what I've quickly sketched out above: see the works by Gary Webb, Nicholas Shou, Robert Parry, and Cockburn and St. Clair's book 'Whiteout'.  For a deeper understanding of the progressive movements in Central America in the 1970s and early '80s, see the books and articles by James Petras, Michael Parenti and Noam Chomsky.  Also see the dynamite movies "Salvador" by Oliver Stone, and the film "Romero."
